results.problem_statement:
Background:  

Consider the one-dimensional $t$-$V$ model of spinless fermions at half filling on a $2N$-site chain with periodic boundary conditions. The Hamiltonian is
\begin{align}
H = & -t \sum_{j=1}^{2N} (a_j^\dagger a_{j+1} + a_{j+1}^\dagger a_j) \\
& + V \sum_{j=1}^{2N} \left(a_j^\dagger a_j - \frac{1}{2}\right)\left(a_{j+1}^\dagger a_{j+1} - \frac{1}{2}\right).
\end{align}
Let $t>0$, and define $a_j = a_{j+2N}$.

In the limit $V \gg t$ (strong repulsion), a variational ground state can be constructed in the Wannierized mean-field basis of fermion operators $c_j$, which are arranged so that the symmetry-broken mean-field state is
\begin{equation}
|\mathrm{MF}\rangle = c_2^\dagger c_4^\dagger \cdots c_{2N}^\dagger |0\rangle.
\end{equation}
Define the "tetramer disruption" operator
\begin{equation}
T = \sum_{j=1}^N \left( c_{2j} c_{2j+1}^\dagger c_{2j+2} c_{2j+3}^\dagger + c_{2j-1}^\dagger c_{2j} c_{2j+1}^\dagger c_{2j+2} \right),
\end{equation}
where $c_{j} \equiv c_{j+2N}$.

The Coupled Cluster ansatz for the ground state is
\begin{equation}
|\alpha\rangle = \exp(\alpha T) |\mathrm{MF}\rangle
\end{equation}
with variational parameter $\alpha \sim (t/V)^2$. Let $Q_{jj'} = \langle \alpha | c_j^\dagger c_{j'} | \alpha \rangle / \langle \alpha | \alpha \rangle$ denote the covariance matrix in the $c_j$ basis. In the thermodynamic limit $N \to \infty$, the expectation value $Q_{1,1+4l}$ can be expressed in terms of a real root $\zeta_0$ of the quartic equation $1 - \zeta - \alpha^2 \zeta^4 = 0$ that lies inside the unit circle. (Specifically, $\zeta_0$ is defined as the unique real root with $|\zeta_0| < 1$; it can be found explicitly by Ferrari's formula for quartic equations or by standard root-finding techniques.)

Task:

Derive, in exact closed form, the value of $Q_{1,1+4l}$ in the thermodynamic limit $N \to \infty$, in terms of $\zeta_0$ and $l$. Your answer should not involve sums over $N$.

