o4-mini.solution:
For a node of degree \(k\) the Boolean sensitivity \(\mathrm{BS}_k\) is by definition the fraction of the \(k+1\) input‐bits (the central bit \(s_i\) plus its \(k\) neighbors) whose flipping on average changes the output of \(\phi\).  If we average uniformly over all \((s_i,\{s_j\}_{j\in N(i)})\), it is most compactly written as

\[
\mathrm{BS}_k
\;=\;
\frac{1}{(k+1)\,2^{\,k+1}}
\sum_{s=0}^1
\sum_{q=0}^k
\binom{k}{q}
\Biggl[
\underbrace{\bigl|\phi\bigl(s,\tfrac{q}{k}\bigr)\;-\;\phi\bigl(1-s,\tfrac{q}{k}\bigr)\bigr|}_{\displaystyle \text{identity‐flip contribution}}
\;+\;
\underbrace{(k-q)\,\bigl|\phi\bigl(s,\tfrac{q}{k}\bigr)\;-\;\phi\bigl(s,\tfrac{q+1}{k}\bigr)\bigr|
\;+\;
q\,\bigl|\phi\bigl(s,\tfrac{q}{k}\bigr)\;-\;\phi\bigl(s,\tfrac{q-1}{k}\bigr)\bigr|
}_{\displaystyle \text{neighbor‐flip contribution}}
\Biggr].
\]

Here  
 • \(\binom{k}{q}/2^{k}\) is the probability to have exactly \(q\) ones among the \(k\) neighbors,  
 • \(\bigl|\phi(s,\rho)-\phi(s',\rho')\bigr|\) is 1 if the two outputs differ and 0 if they coincide,  
 • the first absolute‐difference term counts the effect of flipping the central bit \(s\mapsto1-s\),  
 • the next two terms count the total effect of flipping one neighbor from 0→1 (there are \(k-q\) of those in a configuration with \(q\) ones) or from 1→0 (there are \(q\) of those).  

All together this is a fully closed–form expression for \(\mathrm{BS}_k\) in terms of \(\phi(s,q/k)\).

